Seen in .NET 6+ and Framework 4.0

### Did it work in .NET Framework?

No

### Did it work in any of the earlier releases of .NET Core or .NET 5+?

_No response_

### Issue description

I noticed this bug when drawing vertical lines, where when zoomed out, the lines appeared "thicker" and "fuzzier" than they should have been. Further review shows that this appears to be when using `Graphics.DrawLines()` with more `PointF` points than image pixels (causing subpixel height offsets) and a `Pen.Width` > 1.5. Higher point counts lead to more drastic results. A naiive implementation of `DrawLines()`, namely calling `DrawLine()` in a for loop, produces the correct expected results.

This is an example image with increasing horizontal variation, comapring `DrawLines()` on the left and a for loop of `DrawLine()` on the right (slower, but the "ground truth").
This is with 3x as many points as pixels (3072 points) and a `Pen.Width of 1.501F`, and each pair of lines represents a maximum variance increase in the range of [0..9]. For this example, the ground truth line has a max variance of 10px, whereas the `DrawLines()` version has pixels spanning 24px peak to peak.

<img width="1024" height="1024" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/c362cc75-1188-4e59-8229-4ba8861bde35" />

I've attached the proof of concept program I used to generate this image and demonstrate the problem. I will do some more digging into the source code to see if I can shed more light into this issue, but wanted to at least capture it for the time being.

### Steps to reproduce

Proof of concept console app that generates an image comparing `DrawLines()` and `DrawLine()`, saves the output to a file, and attempts to open it in the default app. This requires either the [System.Drawing.Common NuGet package](https://www.nuget.org/packages/system.drawing.common/) or `UseWinForms` enabled in the .csproj project and the results are pixel identical.

```using System.Diagnostics;
using System.Drawing; //From System.Drawing.Common nuget package, but same issue is seen in the WinForms source

public class Program
{
    private const int ImageWidth = 1024;
    private const int ImageHeight = 1024;

    public static void Main()
    {
        // Issue presents when pointCount > ImageHeight and worsens with disparity
        // If (pointCount < ImageHeight), there is a slight visual difference in the results, but the increased width is not seen
        int pointCount = (int)(ImageHeight * 0.5F);
        int variationIterations = 10;
        float penWidth = 1.501F; // Issue presents when Pen.Width > 1.5F

        GenerateBitmaps(pointCount, variationIterations, penWidth);
    }

    public static void GenerateBitmaps(int pointCount, int variationIterations, float penWidth)
    {
        //Setup
        Color bgColor = Color.White;
        Color lineColor = Color.Red;
        using Bitmap bitmap = new Bitmap(ImageWidth, ImageHeight);
        using Graphics graphics = Graphics.FromImage(bitmap);
        using Pen pen = new Pen(lineColor, penWidth);
        graphics.Clear(bgColor);
        Console.WriteLine($"Generated image with size {ImageWidth}x{ImageHeight}. Using Pen with width: {penWidth}");

        //Test multiple X Position variations
        for (int i = 0; i < variationIterations; i++)
        {
            float padding = variationIterations * 4;
            float drawLinesX = padding + (i / (float)variationIterations * ImageWidth);
            float drawLinesLoopX = drawLinesX + padding;
            DrawLines(graphics, pen, i, pointCount, drawLinesX, drawLinesLoopX);
        }

        //Save and open file
        string output = @"C:\Temp\DrawLinesTest.png";
        bitmap.Save(output, System.Drawing.Imaging.ImageFormat.Png);
        Console.WriteLine($"Saved to {output}, opening...");
        Process.Start(new ProcessStartInfo(output) { UseShellExecute = true });
    }

    public static PointF[] GetPoints(float xPosition, float variation, int count)
    {
        Random rand = new Random(42);
        PointF GetPointF(int i)
        {
            float x = (xPosition + rand.NextSingle() * variation - variation / 2F);
            float y = ((float)ImageHeight / count) * i;
            return new PointF(x, y);
        }
        return Enumerable.Range(0, count).Select(GetPointF).ToArray();
    }

    private static void DrawLines(Graphics graphics, Pen pen, float variation, int count, float drawLinesX, float drawLinesLoopX)
    {
        PointF[] points = GetPoints(drawLinesX, variation, count);
        PointF[] loopPoints = GetPoints(drawLinesLoopX, variation, count);

        graphics.DrawLines(pen, points);
        for (int i = 1; i < count; i++)
        {
            graphics.DrawLine(pen, loopPoints[i - 1], loopPoints[i]);
        }

        Console.WriteLine($"Drew {count} lines with variation of {variation}px.");
        Console.WriteLine($"DrawLines() at x={drawLinesX} | DrawLine() for loop at x={drawLinesLoopX}");
    }
}```

